 = [[Unifi TV|Unifi Play TV]]\n| online chan 7     = [http://hypptv.tm.com.my/EPG/jsp/webtv/index.jsp Watch online] (Malaysia)\n}}\n'''CBeebies''' is a British [[free-to-air]] television channel owned and operated by the [[BBC]]. It is aimed at young children aged 3 + and was launched on 11 February 2002. It manages an international network supported by subscription services.\n\n==History==\n===Launch===\nThe CBeebies channel launched on 11 February 2002, with the first show to air being ''[[Teletubbies]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/feb/11/broadcasting.bbc|title=What Auntie did next|author=Maggie Brown|date=11 February 2002|access-date=4 April 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The domestic CBeebies channel broadcasts from 6:00&nbsp;a.m. to 7:00&nbsp;pm each day<ref>{{cite web|title=CBeebies - what we do|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/commissioning/tv/articles/cbeebies|publisher=BBC|access-date=4 April 2016}}</ref>\u2013 a result of the channel sharing [[Bandwidth (signal processing)|bandwidth]] with the channel [[BBC Four]] on the [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]] platform. The station was joined in March 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?order=asc&q=cbeebies&svc=9371564#search|title=Search Results - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> by an audio ''CBeebies Radio'', which broadcast for three hours each day on the radio station [[BBC Radio 4 Extra|BBC Radio 7]], however since the station was rebranded as [[BBC Radio 4 Extra]] in April 2011, this obligation has ceased. CBeebies Radio, however, has continued as a feature on the channel's website since 2013, and as a station on [[BBC Sounds]] broadcasting from 6am to 10pm. A magazine called ''CBeebies Weekly'' (now called CBeebies Magazine) was first published in 2006.\n\nSince 27 March 2013, CBeebies has been carried by the [[British Forces Broadcasting Service]], sharing a channel with BFBS Extra.<ref>[http://www.bfbs.com/tv/node/823536 BFBS TV IS CHANGING] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017201105/http://www.bfbs.com/tv/node/823536 |date=17 October 2012 }}</ref> The UK channel is also available in the Republic of Ireland.\n\n==International and Non-English versions==\n[[BBC Studios]] owns and operates the international CBeebies feeds, with most of them operating on a 24-hour schedule.\n\nThe first international launch for the CBeebies channel was in India in May 2007, although the channel was withdrawn at the end of November 2012 due to \"commercial considerations\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2012/11/02/bbc-pulls-plug-on-two-india-channels/|title=BBC Pulls Plug on Two India Channels|author=Will Davies|work=WSJ}}</ref>.  The Polish CBeebies channel was launched in December 2007, while feeds in [[Latin America]], Asia, South Africa and Australia were launched in 2008.\nIn March 2011, the [[Video on demand|on demand]] version of the network was launched in the US and is available on [[Xfinity|Xfinity]].\n\nOn 13 May 2011, CBeebies was launched as a programme block on the channel [[BBC Kids]] in Canada, available on weekdays between 9:00&nbsp;am and 3:00&nbsp;pm. It is serving a similar schedule to the main channel. The block ceased alongside its main channel on 31 December 2018, with some programmes moving to [[Knowledge Network]].\n\nIn April 2015, BBC Worldwide signed with South Korean broadcaster [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] and Japanese broadcaster [[Kids Station]] to launch CBeebies blocks on both channels.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/worldwide/2015/cbeebies-programming-blocks</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, a channel for the [[MENA]] region was launched.\n\nOn 10 March 2017, CBeebies Asia was launched in Taiwan, replacing [[BBC Entertainment]]. CBeebies Asia has already launched in Hong Kong, South Korea, Myanmar, the Philippines, Mongolia, Indonesia, Singapore and Malaysia.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} On 13 April 2017, the localised CBeebies feed for Latin America ceased transmissions along with [[BBC Earth]] and BBC Entertainment.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nOn 5 April 2018, a feed was launched on [[Digiturk]] in Turkey.\n\nIn September 2018 as part of a branding strategy, the unbranded 2 hour children's block on BBC Alba was split into CBeebies Alba and [[CBBC (TV channel)#CBBC_Alba|CBBC Alba]], with the former airing during the first hour and the latter airing during the second hour. This block features its own presentation, presenters and shows all dubbed into [[Scottish Gaelic]].\n\nOn 1 December 2019, The Australian feed launched in New Zealand on [[Sky (New Zealand)|Sky]].\n\n==Management==\nIn the UK, CBeebies is operated by the BBC Children's division and part of [[BBC North]]. The division is also responsible for CBBC and overall strategic responsibility for all of the BBC's domestic services for children rests with the Director of Children's, Alice Webb (since 2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/alice-webb|title=BBC - Alice Webb named as Director, BBC Children's - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> The direction of the domestic CBeebies channel itself rested with [[Kay Benbow]], the last Controller of the channel commissioning all CBeebies content across BBC television, online, interactive TV, and radio.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography \u2013 Kay Benbow|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/biographies/biogs/controllers/kay_benbow.shtml|publisher=BBC Press Office|accessdate=16 October 2011}}</ref> She took over from the first controller [[Michael Carrington (television executive)|Michael Carrington]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jan/27/cbeebies-michael-carrington-bbc-turner |title=Carrington Leaves BBC |date=27 January 2010|work= by Mark Sweney, guardian.co.uk }}</ref> In 2017 it was announced that the CBeebies controller post will close in December 2017 and all content for the CBeebies brand would be commissioned by a new, pan BBC Children's role entitled Head of Content.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tbivision.com/news/2017/07/benbow-exiting-bbc-childrens-shake/776711/|title=Benbow exiting in BBC Children's shake-up - TBI Vision - Page 776711|website=tbivision.com}}</ref>\n\nInternationally, CBeebies is owned by [[BBC Studios]], who operate the brand.\n\n==Presentation==\nThe links between programmes on CBeebies are primarily achieved through the use of [[Continuity (broadcasting)|in-vision continuity]], using presenters to interact with the children. In the UK, links are pre-recorded rather than broadcast live, as is the case on sister channel [[CBBC]]. They were originally pre-recorded from studio TC0 at [[Television Centre, London|BBC Television Centre]] in London, however, moved out in 2008 to [[Teddington Studios]], and returned briefly in 2010. From September 2011, the links have been based at the BBC's Northern base at [[Dock10 (television facility)|Dock10]], [[MediaCityUK]], following the move of the BBC Children's department there. International variants feature broadcast links produced either in the corresponding country or from a central base.\n\n===Logo and idents===\n{{main|CBBC idents}}\n\n{{see also|History of BBC television idents}}\n\n===Presenters===\n\nAs well as hosting some of the shows, a number of presenters fill the gaps between the CBeebies shows, speaking directly to the child, leading activities based on a topic from the CBeebies website, showing viewers' birthday cards, and introducing the shows. Many of the presenters have histories as characters on other services or on children's programmes.\n\nIn the UK, presenters seen on the channel and the stranded service are:\n* [[Andy Day]] (2007\u2013present)\n* [[Katy Ashworth]] (2011\u2013present)\n* [[Cat Sandion]] (2013\u2013present)\n* [[Rebecca Keatley]] (2014\u2013present)\n* [[Ben Cajee]] (2015\u2013present)\n* [[Warrick Brownlow-Pike|Dodge T. Dog]] (2015\u2013present)\n* [[Evie Pickerill]](2018\u2013present)\n* [[Nigel Clarke]] (2020-present)\n\nFormer presenters:\n* [[Sue Monroe]] (2002\u20132006)\n* [[Nicole Davis (presenter)|Nicole Davis]] (2003\u20132006)\n* [[Justin Fletcher]] (2006\u20132007)\n* [[Sarah-Jane Honeywell]] (2006\u20132007)\n* [[Eva Alexander]] (2006\u20132007)\n* [[Chris Jarvis (presenter)|Chris Jarvis]] (2002\u20132009)\n* [[Pui Fan Lee]] (2002\u20132009)\n* [[Sidney Sloane]] (2002\u20132013)\n* [[Alex Winters]] (2009\u20132015)\n* [[Cerrie Burnell]] (2009\u20132017)\n* [[Ryan Russell (presenter)|Ryan Russell]] (2017\u20132019)\n\nThe longest serving member is Andy Day who has introduced the programmes, along with most of the other presenters, for just over a decade (12 years).\n\nThe international variants feature different personalities per broadcast region.\n*The Australian feed is the only non-UK CBeebies service to feature more than one presenter, as this feed features 3 presenters. [[Tara Colegrave]] has presented since the channel's launch in 2008<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/perthnow/story/0,,24571433-5005382,00.html|title=TV Guide: Cross to British channels|last=Ganska|first=Helen|date=29 October 2008|work=[[The Sunday Times (Western Australia)|Perth Now]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=13 October 2009|location=Perth, Australia}}</ref> and when the continuity links moved from the UK to Australia, she was joined by [[Robbie Harding]] and [[Duncan Fellows]] in 2011.\n*The Asian feed shown in countries like Thailand, [[Hong Kong]] and Singapore has [[Nisha Anil]] is the main presenter.<ref name=\"te-africa-host\"/><ref name=\"bbc-pr-polish-host\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/bbcworldwide/worldwidestories/pressreleases/2008/04_april/cbeebies_poland.shtml|title=New Polish host for CBeebies revealed|date=4 April 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=13 October 2009|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/bbcworldwide/worldwidestories/pressreleases/2007/10_october/now_tv.shtml|title=BBC Global Channels Asia-Pacific launches three channels on Hong Kong's now TV|last=Castle-Young|first=Amy|date=11 October 2007|publisher=BBC|accessdate=13 October 2009}}</ref> \n*The now-defunct Latin American feed variant had [[Roser Caba\u00f1as]] as the presenter.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/bbcworldwide/worldwidestories/pressreleases/2009/10_october/roser_cabanas.shtml|title=CBeebies unveils first presenter for Latin American and US Hispanic audiences|date=2 October 2009|work=Press Office|publisher=BBC|accessdate=13 October 2009|location=London, UK}}</ref> \n*The Polish channel has had [[Aneta Bo\u017cena Piotrowska]] as main presenter since its launch in 2008. On some occasions between November 2014 to 2016 Aneta appeared on the UK channel.<ref name=\"bbc-pr-polish-host\"/><ref name=\"poland\">[[:pl:CBeebies|Polish Wikipedia ''Cbeebies'' article]]{{Circular reference|date=April 2019}}</ref> \n*The South African feed utilises former UK presenter Sid Sloane.<ref name=\"te-africa-host\">{{cite news|url=http://www.totalexposure.co.za/pressrooms/article.php?a_id=283|title=New Host for CBeebies Africa Revealed|date=8 December 2008|publisher=Total Exposure|accessdate=13 October 2009|location=Johannesburg, South Africa|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722214701/http://www.totalexposure.co.za/pressrooms/article.php?a_id=283|archivedate=22 July 2011}}</ref> Cat Sandion also presented on this feed before becoming a presenter on the UK version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bbc.co.uk/blogs/cbeebiesgrownups/entries/e8f1de10-cd30-334c-8fea-623c12366e24|title=Get to know CBeebies' knew presenter: Cat|website=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*The CBeebies Alba block on [[BBC Alba]] uses Bard Cornark and Carrie Macneil as the presenters.\n\n===Stranded Segments===\n{{overly detailed|section|date=August 2014}}\nIn the UK, the CBeebies channel uses stranded segments throughout the day.\n\nOn 10 March 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/cbeebies/2003-03-10#at-18.00|title=CBeebies - 10 March 2003 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> a segment called the Bedtime Hour was aired.\n\nFrom 3 April<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/cbeebies/2004-04-03#at-13.00|title=CBeebies - 3 April 2004 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> to 19 December 2004, each weekend afternoon was divided into five segments, which were presented by one of the then-current presenters, namely [[Chris Jarvis (presenter)|Chris Jarvis]], [[Nicole Davis (presenter)|Nicole Davis]], [[Pui Fan Lee]], [[Sidney Sloane]] and [[Sue Monroe]]. Each was given a core theme (for instance Sid's segment included \"building and making\" programmes such as ''[[Bob the Builder]]'', Sue's included arts and crafts theme programmes and so on). The five segments aired from 1:00&nbsp;pm until 6:00&nbsp;pm; the segmentation was later dispensed in December 2004, although the presenters still wore their respective colours for several months afterwards. They also cropped up in props used in links, such as coloured plates.\n\nThe five coloured room sections ran from 1:00&nbsp;pm to 6:00&nbsp;pm and included the following:\n* '''Pui's Exploring Hour (Red Room)''', with programmes such as ''[[Come Outside]]'', ''[[Teletubbies|Teletubbies Everywhere]]'', ''[[Tots TV]]'', ''[[Boo! (TV series)|Boo!]]'', ''[[Bits and Bobs]]'', and ''[[Fab Lab]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Pui's+Exploring+Hour&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00:00&tt=00:00#search|title=Search Results - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n* '''Sid's Fix-It Hour (Green Room)''', with programmes such as ''[[Bob the Builder]]'', ''[[Fireman Sam]]'', ''[[Little Robots]]'', and ''[[Postman Pat]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Sid's+Fix+It+Hour&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00:00&tt=00:00#search|title=Search Results - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n* '''Chris's Singalong Hour (Blue Room)''', with programmes such as ''[[Tweenies]]'', ''[[Zingalong]]'', and ''[[Balamory]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?q=Sing-along&svc=9371512#search|title=Search Results - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n* '''Sue's Make and Do Hour (Pink Room)''', with programmes such as ''[[SMarteenies]]'', ''[[Tikkabilla]]'', ''[[Pingu]]'', and ''[[Big Cook, Little Cook]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Make+and+do+hour&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00:00&tt=00:00#search|title=Search Results - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n* '''Nicole's Furry Friends Hour (Orange Room)''', with programmes such as ''[[Clifford the Big Red Dog (TV series)|Clifford the Big Red Dog]]'', ''[[The Koala Brothers]]'', ''[[Angelmouse]]'', ''[[Becky and Barnaby Bear|Barnaby Bear]]'', ''[[Binka]]'', and ''[[The Magic Key]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?q=Furry+Friends+&svc=9371512#search|title=Search Results - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nA new strand entitled the Carrot Club was introduced in 2003, which had a female voiceover presenting where we are shown to toddlers running around and playing with toys. A new strand entitled Pic and Play was shown for the first time in June 2004,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?order=asc&q=pick+and+play&svc=9371512#search|title=Search Results - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> in which viewers contacted CBeebies via the website and other means to suggest programmes they would like to see. Also, in September 2005,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?order=asc&q=bear+and+butterfly&svc=9371512#search|title=Search Results - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> a new strand called Bear and Butterfly launched, showing on weekend mornings. Presented by a cartoon bear (voiced by [[Chris Jarvis (presenter)|Chris Jarvis]]) and butterfly (voiced by [[Sue Monroe]]), and with an occasional appearance from a caterpillar, the characters interacted in an animated environment. They also showed pictures that had been sent in on their Message Tree.\n\nNew strands were introduced on 3 April 2006; Get Set Go from 7:00&nbsp;am to 9:00&nbsp;am, Explorers from 9:00&nbsp;am to 10:00&nbsp;am and 1:00&nbsp;pm to 2:00&nbsp;pm, Busy Beebies from 10:00&nbsp;am to 11:45&nbsp;am and 2:00&nbsp;pm to 3:45&nbsp;pm, Story Corner from 11:45&nbsp;am to 12:00&nbsp;pm and 3:45&nbsp;pm to 4:00&nbsp;pm and Little Lunchers from 12:00&nbsp;pm to 1:00&nbsp;pm. The Bedtime Hour was retained.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/cbeebies/2006-04-03|title=CBeebies - 3 April 2006 - BBC Genome|website=genome.ch.bbc.co.uk|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March 2007,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/mar/19/mondaymediasection9|title=Doing it for the kids|last=Rouse|first=Lucy|date=19 March 2007|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 July 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> these segments were dropped (apart from Get Set Go and Bedtime Hour) and modified to denote the time of day and the levels of activity, including:\n\n* '''Get Set Go''' \u2013 Early morning schedule between 6:00am and 9:00am; retained from 2006 and given longer hours. Includes programmes such as ''[[Something Special (TV series)|Something Special]]'', ''[[Baby Jake]]'', ''[[Twirlywoos]]'', ''[[Raa Raa the Noisy Lion]]'', ''[[Postman Pat]]'', ''[[Bing (TV series)|Bing]]'', ''[[Hey Duggee]]'', ''[[Tinpo]]'', ''[[Biggleton]]'', ''[[Justin's House]]'', ''[[Octonauts]]'' and ''[[Go Jetters]]''. \n* '''Discover and Do''' \u2013 Late morning and early afternoon, weekdays between 9:00&nbsp;am and 3:00&nbsp;pm. The strand is aimed at young children who would not be attending school or pre-school. It often contains programmes that give a learning opportunity to viewers, such as ''[[Show Me Show Me]]'', ''[[Let's Play (TV series)|Let's Play]]'', ''[[Andy's Baby Animals]]'', ''[[Teletubbies]]'', ''[[My First]]'', ''[[Alphablocks]]'', ''[[Numberblocks]]'' & ''[[Yakka Dee]]''. The hour between 12:00&nbsp;pm and 1:00&nbsp;pm is branded as Lunch Time and features shows such as ''[[My World Kitchen]]'', ''[[Molly and Mack]]'' & [[Patchwork Pals]].\n* '''Big Fun Time''' \u2013 Late afternoon weekdays between 3:00&nbsp;pm and 5:45&nbsp;pm. This strand is notable for aiming at the higher end of its remit, airing programming for children who have recently returned from school. Programmes include ''[[Swashbuckle]]'', ''[[Do You Know? (TV series)|Do You Know?]]'', ''[[Andy's Safari Adventures]]'', ''[[Apple Tree House]]'', ''[[Catie's Amazing Machines]]'', ''[[Bitz & Bob]]'', ''[[Waffle the Wonder Dog]]'' & ''[[Gigglebiz]]''. \n* '''Bedtime''' \u2013 The final hour and 15 minutes of CBeebies broadcasting between 5:45&nbsp;pm and 7:00&nbsp;pm. The original stranded section of the channel (and the only to still air to this day), Bedtime helps to prepare children for bed and features calm-natured programming. Programmes include ''[[Clangers]]'',  ''[[Moon & Me]]'',  ''[[Charlie and Lola (TV series)|Charlie and Lola]]'', ''[[Tee and Mo]]'' and ''[[In the Night Garden...]]'' Story-telling is often told during the programmes. The final programme is always the ''Bedtime Stories'' slot (see below) and is followed by a final song, \"The Time Has Come to Say Goodnight\", before the channel closes for the day and [[BBC Four]] starts up. CBeebies Bedtime was renamed from Bedtime Hour as of 4 February 2019.\n\nWhen these segments were initially introduced, each segment featured its own presenting team and set, with [[Chris Jarvis (presenter)|Chris Jarvis]] and [[Pui Fan Lee]] ([[Alex Winters]] and [[Cerrie Burnell]] after they left in January 2009) presenting '''Discover and Do''' in the CBeebies \"living room\"; '''Lunch Time''' in the \"kitchen\"; '''Bedtime Hour''' in the \"bedroom\"; [[Sidney Sloane]] (plus [[Andy Day]] when he joined the channel later in 2007) presenting '''Get, Set, Go!''' in the \"living room\" and '''Big Fun Time''' in the \"garage\". However, since moving production to Manchester this is no longer the case, with the exception of '''Bedtime Hour''' which is presented from the area nearest the house's bed.\n\n[[File:Bedtime Hour.jpg|200px|thumbnail|right|The Bedtime Hour on-screen ident from March 2003 to March 2016.]]\n\n===Storytimes===\nWhile the lunchtime story is usually read by one of the regular presenters, the final show of each day, the ''Bedtime Story'' (known as ''St\u00f2iridh'' in Gaelic) is read by a guest storyteller, including well known actors, comedians, and past presenters of BBC children's television (Like [[Derek Jacobi|Sir Derek Jacobi]] who Narrated all 100 episodes of 2007's ''[[In the Night Garden...]]'' when he appeared in April 2018 and again in June 2018). Some notable storytellers in this slot have included [[James McAvoy]], [[Simon Pegg]], [[David Hasselhoff]], [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]], [[Damian Lewis]], [[Rosamund Pike]], [[Toby Stephens]], [[David Tennant]], [[Ben Faulks]], [[Michael Rosen]], [[Floella Benjamin]], [[Shayne Ward]], [[Chris Evans (actor)|Chris Evans]], [[Big Bird]], [[Tom Hardy]], [[David Schwimmer]], [[Dolly Parton]] and [[Elton John|Sir Elton John]].\n\nIn an unusual move, [[James Bolam]] appeared on \"Bedtime Story\" in costume and in character as Grandpa from ''[[Grandpa in My Pocket]]'', not as himself.\n\nLesser-known storytellers James Blishen and Elliot King have appeared in and taken inspiration from CBeebies' storytime slot, with a programme for James in pre-planning called 'Storytime with James'.{{Citation needed|reason=Cannot find any evidence for this|date=April 2019}}\n\n==CBeebies HD==\nOn 16 July 2013, the BBC announced that a [[High-definition television|high-definition]] (HD) [[simulcast]] of CBeebies would be launched by early 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-23326709 |title=BBC to launch five new HD channels |publisher=BBC News |date=16 July 2013 |accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref> The channel launched on 10 December 2013, though was rolled-out nationwide up to June 2014 (as did [[BBC News (TV channel)|BBC News HD]] and BBC Four HD).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/new-hd-channels.html|title=BBC to launch five new subscription-free HD channels on Tuesday 10 December|publisher=BBC|date=9 December 2013|accessdate=9 December 2013}}</ref> The channel broadcasts on the BBC's new HD multiplex on Freeview and shares its stream with [[BBC Four|BBC Four HD]] as they air at different times. Prior to launch, the majority of CBeebies' HD output was broadcast on [[BBC HD]] before its closure on 26 March 2013.\n\n==Other ventures==\n\n===CBeebies website===\n{{see also|BBC Online}}\n\nThe CBeebies website coincided with the launch of the UK channel in February 2002 and showcases a child friendly site with activities themed to all CBeebies programmes, past and present, with games, songs and print-outs featuring for nearly all shows. The UK version also features links to [[BBC iPlayer|CBeebies iPlayer]], a child friendly version of the [[BBC iPlayer]] featuring CBeebies programmes only, to CBeebies radio player and a dedicated micro site containing advice for raising children and toddlers called CBeebies Grown-ups, which was relaunched in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cbeebies/|title=CBeebies Website Home Page|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091019031830/http://www.bbc.co.uk/cbeebies/|archivedate=19 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020610/login/cyber.htm|title=BBC's CBeebies|date=10 June 2002|publisher=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|Tribune India]]|accessdate=11 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/archive/web-gadets/2002/02/15/beeb-s-a-boon-for-the-kids-115875-11620677/|title=Beeb's a Boon for the Kids |date=15 February 2002|work=The [[Daily Mirror]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|accessdate=11 October 2009|location=London, UK}}</ref>\n\nThe international channels and associated websites are run by [[BBC Studios]]. As a result, not all of them are the same and some channels have less extensive websites than other services. CBeebies channels in Asia, Australia, Poland, South Africa and the USA all have their own international variant.\n\n===VHS and DVD releases===\n[[BBC Video]] (and later [[2Entertain]]) have released several VHS/DVD compilations featuring shows airing on CBeebies at the time. As of 2014, [[Abbey Home Media]] releases the compilations.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!VHS or DVD title\n!Release date\n!Programmes and Episodes\n|-\n| ''CBeebies: The Best of Pre-School Television''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |28 October 2002\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |Fimbles: Tambourine, Tweenies: Invitations, Bill and Ben: Around and Around, Andy Pandy: A Noisy Supper, Teletubbies Everywhere: Ice Skating (Finland)\n|-\n| ''Playtime: Introducing Tikkabilla''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |4 October 2004\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |Tikkabilla in a 45-minute special, Bill and Ben: Go Fly a Kite/A Piece of Sky, Tweenies: Champions, Yoho Ahoy: Pancake with Poop/Paint with Booty, Little Robots: A Bit of Give and Take/By Myself, Andy Pandy: Rub-A-Dub/Potato Prints \nNOTE: This VHS/DVD also has the Andy Pandy song Honey in it, which comes after Rub-A-Dub.\n|-\n| ''CBeebies: The Ultimate Party Collection''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |16 April 2007\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |Big Cook Little Cook: Postman, Bobinogs: Happy Bobi-Birthday, The Roly Mo Show: Little Bo's Birthday, Higgledy House: Birthday, Charlie and Lola: Th