ll|([[Service number|PA-5146]])}}{{rp|208}}<ref name=\"The Gazette of Pakistan\" />\n | commands        = [[XI Corps (Pakistan)|XI Corps]], [[Peshawar]]<br />[[Director-General|DG]] [[Military Intelligence (Pakistan)|Military Intelligence]]<br />[[Structure of the Pakistan Army|16th Infantry Division]] in [[Pano Aqil]]<br />[[Pakistani military deployments|Pakistan Armed Forces\u2013Middle East Command]]\n | battles         = [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]]<br />[[2001-2002 India-Pakistan standoff|India-Pakistani standoff 2001]]<br />[[War on Terror]]<br />[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br />\n*[[Fall of Kabul]]\n*[[Battle of Tora Bora]]\n[[War in North-West Pakistan]]\n*[[Battle of Wanna]]\n*[[Waziristan Accord|Tribal war in Waziristan]]\n | mawards         = [[File:Order of Excellence Nishan-e-Imtiaz.png|25px]]{{small|[[Nishan-e-Imtiaz|Nishan-e-Imtiaz (military)]]}}<br />[[File:Crescent of Excellence Hilal-e-Imtiaz.png|30px]]{{small|[[Hilal-e-Imtiaz|Hilal-e-Imtiaz (military)]]}}<br />[[File:Spange des K\u00f6nig-Abdulaziz-Ordens.png|30px]]{{small|[[Order of King Abdulaziz]]}}<br />[[File:Legion Honneur Chevalier ribbon.svg|30px]]{{small|[[Legion of Honour]]}}\n | military_blank1 = \n | military_data1  = \n | military_blank2 = \n | military_data2  = \n | military_blank3 = \n | military_data3  = \n | military_blank4 = \n | military_data4  = \n | military_blank5 = \n | military_data5  = \n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n | module          = \n | module2         = \n | module3         = \n | module4         = \n | module5         = \n | footnotes       = \n}}\n[[General officer|General]] '''Ehsan ul Haq''' ({{lang-ur|{{nq|\u0627\u062d\u0633\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642}}}}; b. 22 September 1949) {{small|[[Nishan-e-Imtiaz|NI(m)]]}}, {{small|[[Hilal-e-Imtiaz|HI(m)]]}}, {{small|[[Order of King Abdulaziz|OKA]]}}, {{small|[[Legion of Honour|LOH]]}}, is a retired [[four-star general|four-star]] rank [[Pak Fauj|army general]] in the [[Pakistan Army]] and a [[Public Official|public official]], served as the [[Chairman Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee (Pakistan)|Chairman]] of the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee]], appointed on October 2005 until his retirement in 2007.<ref name=\"Centre for Pakistan and Gulf Studies , 2018\">{{cite web|last1=CPAK Gulf|first1=staff writers|title=Profile: Gen.Ehsan ul Haq|url=http://cpakgulf.org/team/gen-r-ehsan-ul-haq-ni-m/|website=cpakgulf.org|accessdate=5 March 2018|location=Islamabad|language=en-pak}}</ref>\n\nAfter retiring from his 40 years of [[military service]], Ehsan ul Haq engaged in the [[Corporate sector of Pakistan|corporate sector]] where he [[Business Management|managed]] the businesses in the [[Healthcare in Pakistan|healthcare industry]], and often offers his [[public speaking]] skills on the issues of [[Foreign policy of Pakistan|foreign policy]] of [[Pakistan]] concerning the [[Pakistan\u2013Arab relations|Arab League]].<ref name=\"Centre for Pakistan and Gulf Studies , 2018\"/>\n\n==Biography==\n\nEhsan ul Haq was born in [[Mardan]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa]] in [[Pakistan]], into a [[Pashto language|Pashto-speaking]] family on 22 September 1949.<ref name=\"Pride of Pakistan press\">{{cite web|title=Gen. (retd) Ehsan ul Haq {{!}} PrideOfPakistan.com|url=https://www.prideofpakistan.com/who-is-who-detail/839|website=/www.prideofpakistan.com/|publisher=Pride of Pakistan press|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> He was educated at the [[PAF Public School Sargodha|PAF Public School]] in [[Sargodha]], a school under the administration of the [[PAF Schools and Colleges|Air Force Education Command]], and [[Matriculation in Pakistan|matriculated]] in 1967.<ref>[http://www.ppss.edu.pk/achievements.htm 'PAF College Sargodha Alumni'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070306201557/http://www.ppss.edu.pk/achievements.htm |date=2007-03-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Hugh Catchpole|url=http://pafcollegesargodha.com/pages/display/56/1|website=pafcollegesargodha.com|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Centenary celebrations of Catchpole open|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/251359|work=DAWN.COM|date=12 June 2007}}</ref> He joined the [[Pakistan Army]] in 1967, and was directed to attend the [[Pakistan Military Academy]] (PMA) in [[Kakul]] where he [[Passing out (military)|passed out]] in the class of 41st PMA Long Course from the academy in 1969.<ref name=\"Speaker's Academy\">{{cite web|last1=Academy\u00ae|first1=Speakers|title=General Ehsan ul Haq (retd.) - Speakers Academy vindt de beste spreker en dagvoorzitter voor uw bijeenkomst.|url=https://www.speakersacademy.com/en/speaker/general-ehsan-ul-haq-retd/|website=www.speakersacademy.com|publisher=Speaker's Academy|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> [[Second lieutenant (United Kingdom)|2nd-Lt.]] Ehsan was [[Commissioned officer|commissioned]] in the [[Army Air Defence Command (Pakistan)|Army Air Defence Command]], and serving in the [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1971|Western front of the third war]] with India in 1971.<ref name=\"Brookings\">{{cite web|title=A Conversation with Gen. Ehsan ul-Haq|url=https://www.brookings.edu/events/a-conversation-with-gen-ehsan-ul-haq/|website=Brookings|publisher=Brookings|accessdate=14 March 2018|date=}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Indo-Pakistani war of 1971|war]] with India in 1971, he went to attend the [[National Defence University, Islamabad|National Defence University]] in [[Islamabad]] where he attained [[Master of Science|MSc]] in [[War Studies]] in 1977.<ref name=\"Centre for Pakistan and Gulf Studies   \u00bb Gen (R) Ehsan ul Haq, NI (M)\"/> In addition, Ehsan also went to attend the [[Command and Staff College]] in [[Quetta]] in 1977 where he was qualified as [[Psc (military)|psc]] in 1980.{{rp|208}}<ref name=\"The Gazette of Pakistan\">{{cite book|title=The Gazette of Pakistan|date=1980|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ydJPAQAAMAAJ&dq=Ehsan+Ul+Haq+PSc&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Ihsan-ul-Haq|accessdate=14 March 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Centre for Pakistan and Gulf Studies   \u00bb Gen (R) Ehsan ul Haq, NI (M)\">{{cite web|title=Gen (R) Ehsan ul Haq, NI (M)|url=http://cpakgulf.org/team/gen-r-ehsan-ul-haq-ni-m/|website=cpakgulf.org|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nEhsan was noted as a specialist in [[anti-aircraft warfare]], having educated and graduated master's degree from the [[PLA Air Force Aviation University]] in [[Zhengzhou]] in [[China]].<ref name=\"Centre for Pakistan and Gulf Studies   \u00bb Gen (R) Ehsan ul Haq, NI (M)\"/>\n\n===War and command appointments in the military===\nIn 1977, [[Major (United Kingdom)|Major]] Ehsan was posted with the [[Pakistan military presence in other countries|Pakistan Armed Forces-Middle East Command]] where he first served as an instructor to the [[Islamic Republic of Iran Air Force|Iranian Air Force]] as an [[exchange officer]] until 1980.<ref name=\"Centre for Pakistan and Gulf Studies \u00bb Gen (R) Ehsan ul Haq, NI (M)\" /> However, [[Major (United Kingdom)|Maj.]] Ehsan left his instructing assignment [[Islamic Republic of Iran Air Force|Iranian IAF]] before the start of the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]], and was posted with a command deputation to the [[Royal Saudi Air Defense]] which he served until 1983\u201384.<ref name=\"Centre for Pakistan and Gulf Studies \u00bb Gen (R) Ehsan ul Haq, NI (M)\" /> In 1986, Ehsan went to the [[United States]] where he attended the [[United States Army]]'s [[United States Army Logistics Management College|Logistics Management College]] in [[Fort Lee (Virginia)|Fort Lee]] in [[Virginia]] and graduated from there in 1989.<ref name=\"Pride of Pakistan press\" />\n\nIn 1990, [[Brigadier (United Kingdom)|Brig.]] Ehsan commanded the 117th Infantry Brigade, later 46 AD Brigade and Deputy Military Secretary in GHQ until 1994 when he was promoted to [[Two-star rank|two-star]] rank and commanded the [[Army Air Defence Command (Pakistan)|3rd Air Defence Division]] until 1996.<ref name=\"Defence Intelligence Agency, 2002\" /> [[Major-General]] Ehsan later took over the command of the [[Structure of the Pakistan Army|16th Infantry Division]] stationed in [[Pano Aqil]] in [[Sindh]] as its [[General officer commanding|GOC]] which he commanded until 1996\u201397.<ref>\"Missile Firing Competition\" ''Dawn'', December 31, 1997</ref>\n\nAfter the [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|military takeover]] of the [[Government of Pakistan|civilian government]] in 1999, [[Major-General|Maj-Gen]] Ehsan was appointed as the [[Director-General]] of the [[Military Intelligence (Pakistan)|Military Intelligence]] (DGMI) and took the command of the MI from then [[Major-General|Maj-Gen]] [[Jamshed Gulzar Kiani]], remaining in this position until April 2001.{{rp|contents}}<ref name=\"Oxford University Press, Kiessling\">{{cite book|last1=Kiessling|first1=Hein|title=Faith, Unity, Discipline: The Inter-Service-Intelligence (ISI) of Pakistan|date=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-1-84904-863-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y_cgDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT173&dq=ehsan+ul+haq+DG+MI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGkbXGsuvZAhVIMGMKHSPGBp4QuwUILDAA#v=onepage&q=ehsan%20ul%20haq%20DG%20MI&f=false|accessdate=14 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2001, [[Lieutenant-General]] Ehsan was posted as the field commander of the [[XI Corps (Pakistan)|XI Corps]] stationed in [[Peshawar]] but remained in this command capacity until October 2001.<ref name=\"Rediff.com, B. Raman, 2004\">{{cite news|last1=Raman|first1=B.|title=Why Musharraf shuffled his generals|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2004/oct/05raman.htm|accessdate=14 March 2018|work=www.rediff.com|agency=Rediff.com|publisher=Rediff.com, B. Raman|date=5 October 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Director ISI (2001\u201304)==\n===Political engineering and controlled democracy===\n{{Main|Guided democracy|Political engineering|Pakistani general election, 2002|Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|Democracy in Pakistan|Military interventionism}}\nOn 7 October 2001, [[Lieutenant-General|Lt-Gen.]] Ehsan was surprisingly appointed as the [[Director-General of Inter-Services Intelligence|Director-General]] of the [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (DG ISI) as part of a major reshuffle that took place when [[President of Pakistan|President]] [[Pervez Musharraf]] went to [[Termination of employment|dismissed]] his key [[Pak Fauj|army generals]] involved in the [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|military takeover]] in [[1999 in Pakistan|1999]].<ref name=\"Rediff.com, B. Raman, 2004\" /> His appointment was in response of removal of the [[ISI (Pakistan)|ISI]] director, [[Mahmud Ahmed]], after the [[September 11 attacks|terrorist attacks]] took place in the [[United States]] on September 2001 which was followed by the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|American]] [[U.S. military response during the September 11 attacks|invasion]] of [[Taliban-administered Afghanistan|Afghanistan]] on October 2001.<ref name=\"Rediff.com, B. Raman, 2004\" />\n\nAbout his reception and image, the [[United States|American]] [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA) ran his profile in June 2002 that described him as holding \"moderate Islamic views\" and calls him a [[Mentorship|\"''protege''\"]] of President [[President Musharraf]], saying the two men had a \"strong relationship\".<ref name=\"Defence Intelligence Agency, 2002\">{{cite web|last1=DIA report|first1=staff|title=Military Leadership Profile: Lieutenant-General Ehsan ul Haq|url=http://www.dia.mil/FOIA/FOIA-Electronic-Reading-Room/FOIA-Reading-Room-Pakistan/FileId/3998/|website=www.dia.mil|publisher=Defence Intelligence Agency|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, he was described as \"keenly aware of big picture issues with viewing of strong support for the democracy, advocating that Pakistan needs a legitimate civilian democratic government\" and \"open with American officials\".<ref name=\"Defence Intelligence Agency, 2002\"/> According to the DIA, Ehsan believes that Pakistan's policy of engagement with the [[Taliban]] was to eventually moderate the Taliban's behavior.<ref name=\"DIA Report 2002\">http://www.dia.mil/FOIA/FOIA-Electronic-Reading-Room/FOIA-Reading-Room-Pakistan/FileId/39986/</ref> He played a crucial role in apprehending of the [[Ahmed Omar Saeed Sheikh|Omar Sheikh]], a [[British people|British]] terrorist and former [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI-6 agent]], from Karachi in 2002, and knew well aware of his status as the [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI-6]] agent as early as 1999.{{rp|183}}<ref name=\"Oxford University Press, Kiessling 2016\"/>\n\nIn 2002, Ehsan [[Political engineering|politically engineered]] a [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|centrist party]] under [[Chaudhry Shujaat|Shuja'at Hussain]] that opposing both the conservative [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)|PML(N)]] and the leftist [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]], and provided his agency's support to promote the Musharraf's mainstream agenda through the new [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|political party]] in the political platform of the country.{{rp|185}}<ref name=\"Oxford University Press, Kiessling 2016\">{{cite book|last1=Kiessling|first1=Hein|title=Faith, Unity, Discipline: The Inter-Service-Intelligence (ISI) of Pakistan|date=2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=London, UK|isbn=9781849048620|pages=310|edition=1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DWojDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA185&dq=ehsan+ul+haq+general+elections&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQopOy6fLZAhVI5mMKHW2pCEEQuwUINzAC#v=onepage&q=ehsan%20ul%20haq%20general%20elections&f=false|accessdate=17 March 2018|language=en|format=google books|chapter={{small|(\u00a7The ISI under Musharraf)}}}}</ref>{{rp|335}}<ref name=\"PublicAffairs, Hiro 2015\">{{cite book|last1=Hiro|first1=Dilip|title=The Longest August: The Unflinching Rivalry Between India and Pakistan|date=2015|publisher=PublicAffairs|location=U.S.|isbn=9781568587349|pages=473|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xHfNDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA335&dq=ehsan+ul+haq+general+elections&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQopOy6fLZAhVI5mMKHW2pCEEQuwUIMTAB#v=onepage&q=ehsan%20ul%20haq%20general%20elections&f=false|accessdate=17 March 2018|language=en|format=google books|chapter={{small|\u00a7Politicized Musharraf Turns Pragmatic}}}}</ref>\n\nHe played a crucial role in dividing the two mainstream parties, the [[Pakistan Muslim League (N)|PML(N)]] being split towards the [[Pakistan Muslim League (Q)|PML(Q)]] while the [[Pakistan Peoples Party|PPP]] forming the [[Pakistan Peoples Party Parliamentarians|parliamentarians]] under [[Amin Fahim]] to fight off the pressure exerted by Lt-Gen. Ehsan.{{rp|186}}<ref name=\"Oxford University Press, Kiessling 2016\"/> After the [[2002 Pakistani general election|general elections]] held in 2002, the ISI under Ehsan remained politically active to [[Legal Framework Order, 2002|provide political support]] to legitimize [[2004 Pakistani presidential election|presidential elections]] in 2004.{{rp|187}}<ref name=\"Oxford University Press, Kiessling 2016\"/>\n\nIn 2018, it was revealed by Urdu columnist, Mahmood Shaam, that Lt-Gen. Ehsan fiercely opposed the candidacy of [[Fazal-ur-Rehman (politician)|Fazal-ur-Rehman]] and notably pressured the [[Alliance for Restoration of Democracy|ARD]] alliance led by [[Benazir Bhutto]] and ultraconservative [[Muttahida Majlis-e-Amal|MMA]] to withdrew the latter's name in favor of [[Zafarullah Khan Jamali]].<ref name=\"Daily Jang, 2018\">{{cite web|last1=Shaam|first1=Mahmood|title=Jab Molana Fazal Ur Rehman Ko Wazir Azam Na Banne Dya Gaya|url=https://dailyurducolumns.com/datColumn.aspx?ColumnID=68850|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406230112/https://dailyurducolumns.com/datColumn.aspx?ColumnID=68850|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 April 2018|website=Daily Urdu Columns|publisher=Daily Jang|accessdate=6 April 2018|language=ur|date=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Chairman joint chiefs (2004\u201307)==\n===Appointment controversy and violence North-West Pakistan===\n{{Main|Violence in Pakistan 2006\u201309|War in North-West Pakistan|Al-Qaeda in the Indian Subcontinent|Allegations of support system in Pakistan for Osama bin Laden}}\n[[File:Insurg\u00eancia taliban.jpg|thumb|left|290px|[[Taliban insurgency in Pakistan|Taliban insurgency]] in 2009. Gen. Ehsan testified of his [[Waziristan Accord|strategic failure]] to contain the Taliban to end the violence when the [[al-Qaeda]] eventually regroup itself and retreated from Pakistan.<ref name=\"Dawn Newspaper, et.al, 2007\"/>]]\nIn 2004, the [[Government of Pakistan]] confirmed the timely retirement of Gen. [[Aziz Khan (general)|Aziz Khan]] as the [[Chairman Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee|Chairman joint chiefs]], and eventually the race was thought be between Adm. [[Shahid Karimullah|Shahid Karim]] and the senior army generals in the Pakistan Army. In the army department alone, there were eight army generals who were in the race for the promotion of four-star rank appointment alongside with [[Shahid Karimullah|Adm. Shahid Karim]], including with seniority:<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> \n{{div col|colwidth=40em}}\n#[[Admiral|Adm.]] [[Shahid Karimullah|Shahid Karim]],<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> [[Chief of Naval Staff (Pakistan)|Chief of Naval Staff]] headquartered in [[Islamabad]].<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/>\n#[[Lieutenant-General|Lt-Gen.]] [[Hamid Javaid]],<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> [[Principal Staff Officer (Bangladesh)|Principal Staff Officer]] to the [[Aiwan-e-Sadr|Presidency]] in [[Islamabad]].\n#Lt-Gen. Javed Hassan,<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> Field commander of the [[XXX Corps (Pakistan)|XXX Corps]] based in [[Gujranwala]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]].\n#Lt-Gen. [[Munir Hafiez]],<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> Chairman of the [[National Accountability Bureau]] (NAB) in [[Islamabad]].\n#Lt-Gen.l [[Ahsan Saleem Hyat]],<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> Field commander of the [[V Corps (Pakistan)|V Corps]] based in [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]]. \n#Lt-Gen. Tariq Waseem Ghazi,<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> President of [[National Defence University, Pakistan|National Defence University]] in Islamabad.\n#Lt-Gen. Muhammad Akram,<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> Field Commander of the [[II Corps (Pakistan)|II Corps]]  based in [[Multan]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]].\n#Lt-Gen. Syed Parwez Shahid,<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> Field Commander of the [[XXXI Corps (Pakistan)|XXXI Corps]] based in [[Bahawalpur]], [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]].\n#Lt-Gen. Ehsan ul Haq,<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> Director-General of the Inter-Services Intelligence (DG ISI). \n{{Div col end}}\n\nDespite his short-coming of his seniority and qualifications, President Musharraf announced to promote Lt-Gen. Ehsan to the four-star appointment and subsequently superseding the senior most Adm. [[Shahid Karimullah|Shahid Karim]] and eight senior army generals in the Pakistan Army on 7 October 2004.<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/> In the public circles and media, the appointment was commented as \"backdrop of a controversy over President Musharraf's uniform and his continuing as army chief after 31 December 2004.\"<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/><ref>[http://www.dawn.com/2004/10/03/top1.htm 'Appointment of new CJCSC and VCOAS' ]</ref><ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\">{{cite web|last=By Arshad Sharif|title=New JCSC chief, VCOAS appointed|url=http://archives.dawn.com/2004/10/03/top1.htm|work=03 October 2004|publisher=Dawn, 03 October 2004|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref> Regardless, the appointment to four-star appointment was deemed as controversial by the political circles of the country.<ref name=\"Dawn, 03 October 2004\"/>\n\nOn 18 December 2004, Gen. Ehsan was appointed as first ever [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of the [[Army Air Defence Command (Pakistan)|Army Air Defence Command]].<ref>[http://www.presidentofpakistan.gov.pk/PRPresidentDirectiveDetail.aspx?nPRPresidentDirectiveId=83&nYear=2006&nMonth=3 \"Air defense to be modernized says President\"]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''President of Pakistan Press Release'', December 18, 2004</ref> In 2005, Gen. Ehsan went to visit [[China]] to maintain defence ties in a view of strengthening the arm industry.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018Defence ties with China to be strengthened\u2019|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/157298|accessdate=19 March 2018|work=DAWN.COM|date=19 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nAs Chairman joint chiefs, he oversaw the [[War in North-West Pakistan order of battle|troops deployment]] in [[War in North-West Pakistan|tribal areas]] to end the [[Violence in Pakistan 2006\u201309|violence]] and supported his [[Waziristan Accord|plan and strategy]] to gain public support despite the reluctance from the [[United States]] in 2006.<ref name=\"Dawn Newspaper, et.al, 2007\">{{cite news |title=Waziristan truce went wrong: Gen Ehsan|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/274074|accessdate=19 March 2018|work=Dawn.com |publisher=Dawn Newspaper |date=3 November 2007}}</ref> However, in 2007, Gen. Ehsan openly admitted when he testified his failure to end the violence and expulsion of [[Central Asia]]n and [[Afghan Arabs]] in the country noting that, \"the [[al-Qaeda]] and the [[Taliban in Pakistan|Taliban militants]] used the [[Waziristan Accord|2006 peace agreement]] to regroup and carry out terrorist attacks in both [[Pakistan and Afghanistan]].\"<ref name=\"Dawn Newspaper, et.al, 2007\"/>\n\n==Retirement from military==\n===Corporate business and healthcare activities===\nIn 2007, Gen. Ehsan sought his retirement after his testimony in the [[Washington D.C.]] in [[United States]] and went to join the [[Corporate sector of Pakistan|corporate world]] eventually becoming the [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]] of the Pakistan\u2013Libya Holding Company, an investment firm.<ref name=\"Centre for Pakistan and Gulf Studies , 2018\" /> He oversaw the company operations both in [[Libya under Gaddafi|Libya]] and [[Pakistan]] but departed from the investment firm when the [[2011 Libya revolution|revolution]] took place in 2011, and subsequently went to join the [[Healthcare in Pakistan|healthcare industry]] in 2011.<ref name=\"Centre for Pakistan and Gulf Studies , 2018\" />\n\nHe is currently serving as the Chairman of the [[Board of Governors]] of the Al-Shifa Trust, which runs a chain of [[Eye care professional|eye care hospitals]] throughout Pakistan, while also managing the DNA Health Corporation, an American based health company based in [[New York City|New York]].Apart from these he is involved in many different businesses in Pakistan and worldwide. <ref name=\"Centre for Pakistan and Gulf Studies , 2018\" />\n\nIn 2017, Ehsan vehemently criticized the [[Third Sharif ministry|Nawaz administration]] over its [[International reactions to the Saudi-led intervention in Yemen (2015\u2013present)|strict neutrality]], calling for supporting the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|military intervention]] by [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[United Arab Emirates]] in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]].<ref name=\"GEO News, 2017, Safi\">{{cite news|last1=Safi|first1=Saleem|title=Jirga With Saleem Safi: General (R) Ehsan ul Haq Exclusive Interview|url=http://siasiexpress.com/post_siasat/jirga-with-saleem-safi-1st-october-2017-general-r-ehsan-ul-haq-exclusive-interview/|accessdate=26 March 2018|work=Geo TV and GEO News|agency=GEO News|publisher=daily motion|date=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arab\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite news |title=General Ehsan awarded Saudi Arabia's highest civil award|url=http://fp.brecorder.com/2006/03/20060308395280/|accessdate=26 March 2018|work=Business Recorder|date=8 March 2006}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mahmud Ahmed]]}} \n{{s-ttl|title=Director General of the [[Inter-Services Intelligence]]|years=2001\u20132004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ashfaq Parvez Kayani]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Aziz Khan (general)|Aziz Ahmed Khan]]}} \n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chairman Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee (Pakistan)|Chairman Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee]]|years=2004\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tariq Majid]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{CJCSC Pakistan |state=expanded}}\n{{Inter-Services Intelligence}}\n{{Pakistan Army template}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haq, Ehsan ul}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Pashtun people]]\n[[Category:PAF College Sargodha alumni]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Pakistani military personnel of the Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]]\n[[Category:National Defence University, Pakistan alumni]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in Iran]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Urdu\u2013Arabic translators]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in China]]\n[[Category:Chinese\u2013Urdu translators]]\n[[Category:PLA Air Force Aviation University alumni]]\n[[Category:Pakistani aviators]]\n[[Category:Pakistani diplomats]]\n[[Category:Pakistani spies]]\n[[Category:Pakistani generals]]\n[[Category:Directors General of Inter-Services Intelligence]]\n[[Category:Pakistani democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Chairmen Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:People of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:2004 controversies]]\n[[Category:People of the War in North-West Pakistan]]\n[[Category:2007 controversies]]\n[[Category:Pakistani corporate directors]]\n[[Category:Pakistani chief executives]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in Libya]]\n[[Category:Pakistani investors]]\n[[Category:Pakistani financiers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani healthcare managers]]\n[[Category:Middle Eastern studies scholars]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Nishan-e-Imtiaz]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Hilal-i-Imtiaz]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Abdulaziz al Saud]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Honour]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific_prefix   = \n | name               = Ehsan ul Haq\n | native_name        = {{Nobold|{{lang|ur|{{nq|\u0627\u062d\u0633\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642}}}}}}<!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific_suffix   = \n | image              = Ehsan ul haq.jpg \n | image_size         = 260px\n | image_upright      =\n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = \n | caption            = Ehsan ul Haq, [[Circa|ca.]] [[2007 in the United States|2007.]]\n | order              = \n | office             = [[Chairman Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee]]\n | term_start         = 6 October 2004\t\n | term_end           = 7 October 2007\t\n | alongside          = <!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district.  (e.g. United States Senators.)-->\n | monarch            = \n | president          = \n | governor_general   = \n | primeminister      = \n | taoiseach          = \n | chancellor         = \n | governor           = \n | vicepresident      = \n | viceprimeminister  = \n | deputy             = \n | lieutenant         = \n | succeeding         = <!--For President-elect or equivalent-->\n | parliamentarygroup =\n | constituency       = \n | majority           = \n | predecessor        = Gen. [[Aziz Khan (general)|Aziz Khan]]\n | successor          = Gen. [[Tariq Majid]]\n | prior_term         =\n<!----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->\n | order2             = [[Director-General of Inter-Services Intelligence|Director-General of the Inter-Services Intelligence]]\n | office2            =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | term_